        "notes_updates": "Symptoms: Fever or hypothermia, Rigors, Tachypnoea, Confusion/delirium, Reduced urine output, Malaise, Non-specific symptoms (especially elderly)\nSigns: Fever (> 38.3°C) or hypothermia (< 36°C), Tachycardia, Tachypnoea (RR > 22), Hypotension (SBP < 90, MAP < 65), Raised shock index (HR/SBP), Elevated lactate, Altered mental status, Oliguria (< 0.5ml/kg/hr), Skin mottling, Cold peripheries\nRisk factors: Immunocompromise, Diabetes Mellitus, Elderly, Pregnancy, Recent surgery, Indwelling lines/catheters, Chronic organ failure, Malignancy\nInvestigations - bedside: VBG/ABG (lactate, acidosis), Blood glucose, Urine dipstick, Urine βHCG, ECG\nInvestigations - lab: FBC, U&E, CRP, Lactate, Blood cultures (before antibiotics if possible), INR/PTT, LFT\nInvestigations - imaging: CXR (pneumonia), Abdominal ultrasound, CT as indicated by suspected source\nDisposition: ICU consult if requiring continuous inotropes or ventilatory support. Internal Medicine admission for less severe cases.\nWarnings: Surviving sepsis bundles to be completed within 3 hours: measure lactate, obtain blood cultures prior to AB, administer broad spectrum AB, administer 30ml/kg crystalloid bolus for hypotension/lactate > 4; Within 6 hours: apply vasopressors for MAP > 65, reassess volume status if persistent hypotension or lactate > 4, remeasure lactate; Antibiotics within 1 hour - do not delay for cultures if this will delay antibiotics; Young patients may compensate BP until late - isolated raised lactate may be only sign; Elderly may have isolated hypotension and very non-specific lactate levels; Don't wait for fluid bolus to finish before considering inotropic support; Can initiate vasopressors on peripheral line and change to CVP within 6 hours; High index of suspicion in immunocompromised, DM, elderly, pregnant, paediatric patients"
