        "notes_updates": "EPISTAXIS | Important information to note: Duration/frequency/side, Severity & estimated blood loss, Bleeding diathesis, Comorbidities, Current medication (oral/nasal), History of recent trauma | Investigations: Blood tests are not routinely required. Excessive bleeding -> Ward Hb. FBC/INR if: Shocked, Age > 65 years, Pale, On Warfarin, Bleeding disorder | NO evidence between hypertension & epistaxis. Epistaxis is more common in hypertensive patients due to vascular fragility. Epistaxis & the associated anxiety cause an acute elevation in BP | Immediate Management: ABCD approach. Ask patient to blow nose to remove all clots. Sit patient forward & ask them to pinch their nose (press alae firmly against septum) for 10-15 minutes. Patient to spit out excess blood (swallowing will cause vomiting). If bleeding stops -> observe for 30 mins for re-bleeding. If no re-bleeding -> Discharge. TTO: Bactroban ointment apply 8 hourly for 3/7 | Still bleeding / Re-bleed -> Nasal Packing: Oxymetazoline (Iliadin) nasal spray 2 puffs. Anaesthetise prior to packing: Cotton wool soaked in 2% Lignocaine placed into the nose. Nasal nerve block. Merocel Nasal Tampon: Trim tampon if patient has a small nose, Insert along the floor of the nostril, Pack both nostrils -> tamponade, Expand with adrenaline 1:10 000, Leave in situ for 24-48 hours. If no nasal tampons: Soak a 10 x 10 cm piece of gauze in Cyclokapron [500mg/5ml] - insert into bleeding nostril. Pack with ribbon gauze soaked in 1:10 000 adrenaline | Still bleeding? Posterior bleed is likely -> Posterior Nasal Packing: Call a senior doctor. Administer Cyclokapron 15mg/kg (max 1g) IV over 15 min. Remove nasal packing. Insert a Foley's catheter (size 10-14F) along the floor of the nasal cavity until the tip is visualized in the oropharynx. Inflate Foley's bulb with +/-10-20ml of water for injection. Retract catheter gently so that it butts against the posterior palate. Keep catheter in place by clamping with a hemostat. Place gauze around the clamp and between the ala of the nose and the clamp to prevent pressure necrosis. Repack both nostrils. Refer to ENT | CROUP: Assess severity. Clinical diagnosis. CXR only if diagnostic doubt. Minimal handling, position of comfort, defer IV access, avoid distress. Westley Croup Severity Score: 0-2 = Mild; 3-7 = Moderate; 8-11 = Severe; 12+ = Impending respiratory failure. | Mild: Mild distress, No stridor at rest, No/minimal chest wall retractions. Treatment: ALL children with croup require steroids. Prednisolone 1mg/kg PO x 2/7 OR Dexamethasone 0.15mg/kg PO/IM single dose (max 10mg). Budesonide 2mg. No nebulisation or adrenaline needed. O2 only if SATS <93%. Observe 30 min post steroid. | Moderate: Stridor at rest, some retractions. Treatment: Steroids as above. Budesonide 2mg nebulised. Adrenalin (1:1,000) 0.5ml/kg/dose (max 5ml) nebulised, repeated every 15-20 minutes if stridor not improving or worsening. O2 if SATS <93%. Observe 30-60 min. | Severe: Increased stridor, marked retractions, agitation. Treatment: Dexamethasone 0.6mg/kg IM/IV (max 12mg). Budesonide 2mg nebulised. Adrenalin (1:1,000) 0.5ml/kg/dose (max 5ml) nebulised, repeated 15-20 min. Move to resuscitation area. O2 if SATS <93%. Intubate if rapid relapse or no response to adrenaline. Most senior clinician should intubate. Need 2 ET tubes (1 smaller size than usual). Etomidate 0.3mg/kg IVI recommended for induction. | Respiratory Failure: Severe distress, agitation, cyanosis. Treatment: Dexamethasone 0.6mg/kg IM/IV (max 12mg). Budesonide 2mg nebulised CONTINUOUSLY. Adrenalin (1:1,000) 0.5ml/kg/dose (max 5ml) CONTINUOUS nebulisation if in extremis. Resuscitation area. Call for HELP. Most senior clinician must intubate. | Croup Discharge Criteria: Stable vitals, no stridor at rest, normal colour & LOC, tolerating oral fluids, minimum 30 min post steroids, minimum 3 hours post adrenaline, access to transport. Mild distress: own transport. Severe distress/agitation/cyanosis: EMS transport. | Croup Admission Criteria: Absolute: Symptoms persisting >4 hours after steroid administration, Audible stridor at rest, Significant respiratory effort, O2 requirement, Poor response to ED treatment, History of severe obstruction prior to presentation, History of previous severe croup, Known structural airway abnormality. Relative: <6 months, Poor oral intake/dehydration, Social issues, Late evening/night presentation, Uncertain diagnosis | EPIGLOTTITIS: URGENT ENT consult - intubate in theatre. Prepare for emergency cricothyrotomy if must intubate in ED. Defer painful procedures in paediatric patients. Defer X-rays unless diagnostic uncertainty. Ceftriaxone 2g IV stat. Fibreoptic laryngoscopy = gold standard. Avoid supraglottic devices. Dual setup for surgical airway. No benefit to steroids/nebulized adrenaline | ACUTE OTITIS MEDIA: Analgesia first line: oral paracetamol/NSAIDs. Consider topical anaesthetic eardrops if TM intact. Most cases resolve spontaneously - limit use of antibiotics. Antibiotics if: AOM in only hearing ear, cochlear implants. Amoxicillin 45mg/kg BD 5/7 first line. If failure to respond to first line or observation within 48-72 hours: Co-amoxyclav (Augmentin) 22.5mg/kg/dose BD 5/7. Refer ENT if effusion >3 months. Urgent ENT referral for: systemically unwell child, neonate, acute mastoiditis, cochlear implant. TM perforation does not alter management | PHARYNGITIS: 90% viral. Use Modified Centor Score. 0-2: strep unlikely. 2-3: throat culture/rapid strep test. >4: strep likely - antibiotics. Discharge with amoxicillin 50mg/kg 10/7 and good analgesia. Macrolide in penicillin allergy. Admit if: unable to swallow, systemic illness, risk of upper airway obstruction, peritonsillar abscess, diagnostic uncertainty, concern for acute rheumatic fever/glomerulonephritis",
